oakcurric:unit-3105
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Belongings: 'tener' and articles 'un' and 'una'"@en ;
  curric:slug "belongings-tener-and-articles-un-and-una" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn the singular and plural indefinite articles, and that
  nouns have abstract gender. They form plural nouns with -s. Pupils learn the singular
  forms of 'tener' in the context of belongings. Key sounds learnt are ll, l, ca, co, cu."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit adds 'tener' to pupils' early knowledge of highly frequent
  Spanish verbs. Pupils build on their knowledge of gender in Spanish when they learn masculine
  and feminine indefinite articles and nouns. They are introduced to forming plural nouns and
  indefinite articles, and will extend their repertoire of nouns, plural nouns, and determiners
  in later units. Hard c is introduced to a, o, u to expand their knowledge of vowels. New
  sounds l and ll are taught.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3105-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3105-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3105-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3105-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3105-5 ;
  curric:id "3105"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.489846Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-have-having .

oakcurric:unit-3127
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Opinions and feelings: gustar-type verbs, 'ser' and 'estar'"@en ;
  curric:slug "opinions-and-feelings-gustar-type-verbs-ser-and-estar" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces 'gustar'-type verbs in the context of giving opinions about
  something. Exploitation of the text 'Ayaymamá' provides consolidation of ‘ser’ for traits
  and ‘estar’ for state/location. Key sounds revisited are rr, r, silent h."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils learn how to give opinions using 'gustar'-type verbs.
  They build on their existing knowledge of indirect object pronouns 'me', 'te', 'le' and
  object-verb-subject word order. Pupils secure 'ser' for traits and 'estar' for state or
  location by exploiting the text 'Ayaymamá'. Pupils revisit key sounds rr, r, silent h.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3127-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3127-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3127-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3127-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3127-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3127-6 ;
  curric:id "3127"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.492088Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being ,
    oakcurric:thread-read-and-respond-to-texts .

oakcurric:unit-3138
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Sport and healthy living: present continuous, 'vuestro/a'"@en ;
  curric:slug "sport-and-healthy-living-present-continuous-vuestro-a" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces the second person plural form of -ar verbs, which pupils
  contrast with the second person singular. They learn forms 'sois' and 'estáis', and form
  the present continuous using 'estáis'. Second person plural possessive adjective
  'vuestro/a' is introduced in singular forms."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit expands pupils' knowledge of present tense -ar verbs, 'ser' and
  'estar' by adding the second person plural forms. This knowledge enables pupils to form the
  present continuous, which they learned in a previous unit, using 'estáis'. Furthermore,
  pupils learn to use second person plural possessive adjective 'vuestro/a' which they contrast
  with their existing knowledge of possessive adjective 'tu'. In phonics, pupils consolidate
  forming diphthongs with strong and weak vowels, and hiato with two strong vowels.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3138-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3138-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3138-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3138-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3138-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3138-6 ;
  curric:id "3138"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.533361Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-present .

oakcurric:unit-3141
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Countries: 'hacer', -ar verbs"@en ;
  curric:slug "countries-hacer-ar-verbs" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit revisits singular present and preterite forms of 'hacer', and introduces
  the use of 'hacer' with the weather. Pupils learn plural forms '-amos' and '-aron' for -ar
  verbs in the preterite, and contrast these with their singular counterparts and '-amos' in
  the present tense."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils consolidate singular present and preterite forms of
  'hacer'. They build on this knowledge to talk about what the weather is or was like when
  doing activities. Pupils are already familiar with singular forms of -ar verbs in the
  preterite, and now add '-amos' and '-aron' to their repertoire. They refresh singular forms
  by contrasting them with the new plural preterite forms, and also contrast preterite '-amos'
  with present tense '-amos', as this is an area of linguistic difficulty. New sound ch is
  taught, and stress patterns are revisited.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3141-8 ;
  curric:id "3141"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.634764Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-past ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-present .

oakcurric:unit-3104
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Identity: 'estar' and 'ser'"@en ;
  curric:slug "identity-estar-and-ser" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn singular forms of the verb 'estar' to talk about
  location and states, and singular forms of the verb 'ser' to talk about traits. They use
  adjective agreement as a complement to a verb to describe what someone is like, and learn
  sounds for vowels a, e, i, o, u in Spanish."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces pupils to the verbs 'ser' and 'estar', to be for
  location, states, and traits, which is essential early knowledge. Pupils are introduced to
  the concept that some adjectives can change their endings based on gender, which they will
  build on with adjective-noun agreement in a later unit. They learn how to ask questions using
  raised intonation, and with '¿cómo?' and '¿dónde?' to ask where something is or what someone
  is like and to ask for clarification in class. The foundations for learning phonics are laid
  with the sound-symbol correspondences a, e, i, o, u.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3104-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3104-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3104-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3104-4 ;
  curric:id "3104"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.391346Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions .

oakcurric:unit-3106
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Activities: singular -AR verbs in the present tense"@en ;
  curric:slug "activities-singular-ar-verbs-in-the-present-tense" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces infinitive and singular forms of prototypical and top 25
  regular -ar verbs, in the context of talking about what people do. Key sounds learnt are
  cue, cua, cui and ce and ci."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils broaden their knowledge of verbs with the addition of
  singular and infinitive -ar verbs. Pupils reinforce their knowledge of indefinite articles
  and nouns, and combine this knowledge with -ar verbs to form simple sentences, in which they
  add new vocabulary to their repertoire. Pupils build on their knowledge of the sound-symbol
  correspondence cu with new sounds cue, cua, cui, and learn a new way to pronounce c with ce
  and ci.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3106-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3106-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3106-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3106-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3106-5 ;
  curric:id "3106"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.788696Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions .

oakcurric:unit-3119
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "People and places: 'ser' and 'estar'"@en ;
  curric:slug "people-and-places-ser-and-estar" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit consolidates 'ser' for traits and 'estar' for state/ mood in the context
  of people and places now versus in general. Pupils combine these verbs with adjectives,
  practising agreement for gender and number. Weak vowels i and u are combined with strong
  vowels to create diphthongs."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils strengthen 'ser' for traits and 'estar' for state/
  mood in singular and plural persons. They anchor adjective agreement by combining adjectives
  with 'ser' and 'estar' to describe what people and places are like, and they embed the use of
  negatives and questions with these verbs. Pupils are introduced to the concept of weak vowels
  combining with strong vowels to create diphthongs.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3119-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3119-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3119-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3119-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3119-5 ;
  curric:id "3119"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.912266Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being .

oakcurric:unit-3148
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Inspiring people: 3rd person singular and plural preterite"@en ;
  curric:slug "inspiring-people-3rd-person-singular-and-plural-preterite" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit revisits singular forms of regular -ar, -er, -ir verbs and irregular
  verbs in the preterite. It revisits question words, direct object pronouns, and contrasts
  the third person plural present with the preterite. Pupils exploit texts to learn about
  Diana Trujillo."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils consolidate regular and irregular singular verbs in
  the preterite, question words, and direct object pronouns 'lo' and 'la'. Pupils draw on this
  knowledge to help them explore texts about Diana Trujillo. They reactivate the third person
  plural present by contrasting it with the third person plural preterite and anchor this
  knowledge by talking about past and present achievements of engineers. Pupils revisit key
  sounds r and rr, and contrast strong and weak vowels.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3148-8 ;
  curric:id "3148"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.944094Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-past .

oakcurric:unit-3114
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "At home and away: -AR verbs 3rd person plural, 'estar' and 'ser'"@en ;
  curric:slug "at-home-and-away-ar-verbs-3rd-person-plural-estar-and-ser" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit revisits the present tense of -ar verbs and adds the third person plural
  form, which is contrasted with the third person singular. Pupils work with an authentic
  text 'Un hombre sin cabeza' by Armando José Sequera. Pupils revisit modal verbs, 'ser' and
  'estar'."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils anchor their knowledge of -ar verbs and modal verbs
  through understanding of an authentic text. They learn the third person plural form of -ar
  verbs and contrast this with the third person singular which is familiar to them. They
  revisit modal verbs and 'ser' and 'estar' in plural persons. Pupils revisit key sounds z,
  que, qui, ll, l.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3114-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3114-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3114-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3114-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3114-5 ;
  curric:id "3114"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.950314Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
